voice_to_text: A little over one month later I'm back with an update. I wanted to show you how all my little propagations are doing the ones that I stuck in with a cut up golden pothos that you see right here. So, I did this technique with more than I'd originally posted about in the video. As you can see right here, I did it with this Rosemary. I also did it with at least a few different clippings of Flaming Katy… more of which you can see right here. and little gold golden pothos in the back. I've Learned at least a few different lessons I'm gonna share with you from this experiment. The first lesson is that there's some plants that this technique works very well with. This Rosemary for instance— she's doing great got lots of little root growth I'll probably let her go for another month or two. It also really worked well with the flaming Katy’s. With it's originally intended plant it did not work well. It’s quite dead and rotted 🥲 Moment of silence for the fallen 🤧 but so um [Lesson #2] as it turns out from Google no matter what I did this one wouldn't have survived because she needed to have some of her  original root mass to come with her. So, yeah originally she started folding in her  leaves and I'm like “No baby your stem is still great keep holding on.” So I Frankenstein the hell out of her with  some tape to hold her open. Just thinking: “You got this take in that light you're gonna you're gonna survive I swear!”  She didn’t 🥲🥲 No— she eventually just continued to rot and I felt like a terrible person.  Clearly I still have much to learn about  being a plant mom. [Lesson #3]: Though, I would consider this  Rosemary propagation a success, due to where the wax is located it did prevent roots from forming in that specific area. Do with that information what you will 👌💋

voice_to_text: are you a serial plant killer you know what I used to be too until I Learned this one little trick and it's the skewer method now this is a super simple way to check to see if your plants need water or not a lot of the times your plant will die because it's either under watered or overwatered but the skewer method really will just completely change the game when it comes to caring for plants so let me show you how to check so I have this beautiful plant right here and here's my skewer I'm gonna shove this skewer down into this plant and i'mma pull it back out now let's take a look at this skewer now that I pulled it out now if I look at the skewer I can see that dirt stuck to the very bottom of this skewer but if you look at the top part there's nothing stuck to it which tells me that the top half of that soil on that plant is dry the dirt will stick to the skewer where the plant is wet so with this tells me that it's only like the bottom inch to an inch and a half that is wet on this plant which tells me this plant needs water now we're gonna check this one and see what she looks like cause I just gave her some water the other day so she should be a little more wet but let's pull this skewer out and I'm trying to do this with one hand for y'all so you can see what the heck I'm doing oh so look at that one see all the dirt that stuck to this this plant is really good and wet so all that dirt that stuck to it that's telling me it doesn't need water right now now I check my plants like this about twice a week and it's super simple because the skewer will it's gonna tell you if your plant needs water or not and this is one of the simplest and quickest ways that you can check that way you know whether you need to feed your plant or just let it chill out until the next time you check I hope this helps I love y'all have a good

voice_to_text: Random fact that only you know because of your weird, specific job. Let me introduce you to the Victoria water platter, one of the most amazing plants in the world. The Victoria water platters are native to the tropics of South America and related to water lilies. Their leaves grow up to about 4 to 6 feet in diameter. For reference, I'm 6 feet tall here in this picture. One of the coolest things about them is that their flowers actually exhibit thermogenesis. This means that they create their own heat, and they can actually reach temperatures of up to 90 degrees Fahrenheit. We're just getting started. Each flower only blooms for two nights. The first night, the flower is white and female, like you see here. The heat attracts nocturnal beetles, which crawl in through this opening here. The flower provides carbohydrate reserves, which keeps the beetle orgy going all night long. In the morning, the flower closes up, trapping the beetles inside. On the second night, the flower opens as a pink male and begins releasing pollen as a trap. Beetles escape. They move past the anthers, carrying pollen with them to a fresh female flower for round two. They're also covered in insane spine.
